article.description:
Danilo Pinnock scored 15 of his 21
points after halftime and No. 19 George Washington rallied to beat
Marshall 79-73 in overtime Saturday night.
article.headline: Pinnock leads second-half rally as GW escapes with win
article.linkText: Pinnock leads second-half rally as GW escapes with win
article.story: HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Danilo Pinnock saved George Washington from an embarrassing loss. Pinnock scored 13 of his 21 points in the final 4:30 of regulation and in overtime to lift George Washington (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 AP) to a 79-73 win over Marshall. Just three days after George Washington showed patience and poise against Temple's matchup zone in a double-digit victory, the Colonials had to scrap against a Marshall team picked to finish last in its inaugural season in Conference USA. George Washington coach Karl Hobbs freed up the Colonials' leading scorer in the second half for open shots. "During a media timeout, we switched him to our four spot, which gets him slashing down the lane," Hobbs said. "We knew he would pick it up and get us back where we needed to be and he did just that." Pinnock hit four baskets over the final 10 minutes of the game and got Marshall's big men in foul trouble. His basket off a drive with 39 seconds left in overtime gave George Washington a three-point lead. Marshall's leading scorer, Mark Patton, fouled out on the play. "I stood back and watched early, but my teammates put me in position to score," Pinnock said. "I just stepped it up and started attacking the basket more." George Washington was held to one field goal over an eight-minute span of the second half and Marshall went on an 14-2 run for a 51-39 lead with 7:30 left. But free throw shooting would doom Marshall, which made just 18-for-33 for the game. "We came off the media timeout and missed a pair of free throws, so we weren't able to get back in our zone," Marshall coach Ron Jirsa said. "They were able to get off to a running start and they never stopped from there." Pinnock's steal and dunk brought the Colonials within 57-56. Carl Elliott hit a 3-pointer with 12 seconds left in regulation to tie the score at 64, but he then fouled Mark Dorris. The Marshall freshman missed both free throws to send the game into overtime. Patton's 3-point play pulled Marshall within 70-69 with 1:51 left in overtime, but the Thundering Herd quickly lost their patience. After the teams traded baskets, George Washington attempted seven foul shots in a 14-second span. The Colonials scored six straight points, four on free throws, to seal the win. Elliott finished with 18 points before fouling out on the first possession of overtime for George Washington (10-1). Maureece Rice and Pops Mensah-Bonsu had 15 points apiece. Only six players scored for the Colonials. Patton led Marshall (6-6) with 21 points. Markel Humphrey had a career-high 15 points and 10 rebounds. Chris Ross added 11 points. "Coach always said that even though I'm a freshman, I can step up and be a leader," Humphrey said. "I took it to heart tonight. As a team, our chemistry is starting to build and we looked good for 35 minutes tonight." It was the second straight meeting between the teams in which George Washington erased a double-digit lead. In 2001, the Colonials overcame a 19-point deficit in the second half to defeat Marshall 69-64 in the NABC Classic in Lexington, Ky.
